To add a button press effect on click, you can use CSS pseudo-classes like :active and :focus. Here's an example:

.gen-button:active,
.gen-button:focus {
  transform: scale(0.95);
  box-shadow: none;
}

This CSS will make the button scale down slightly and remove any box shadow when it is pressed or in focus. Feel free to adjust the transform and box-shadow properties to achieve the desired effect.

If you want the button to return to its original state immediately after being pressed, you can use the CSS :active pseudo-class along with a transition property. Here's an updated example:

.gen-button {
  /* existing styles */
   transition: transform 0.2s;
}

.gen-button:active,
.gen-button:focus {
  transform: scale(0.95);
  box-shadow: none;
}

This CSS will add a smooth transition effect to the transform property, making the button scale down when pressed, and then return to its original state once the press is released. The button will no longer get stuck in the scaled-down state until you press somewhere else. You can adjust the transition duration (0.2s in this example) to achieve the desired speed.

I apologize for the confusion. If you want to create an onClick button press effect using CSS, you can use keyframes animation. Here's an example:

```css
.gen-button {
  /* existing styles */
  transition: transform 0.1s;
}

.gen-button:active,
.gen-button:focus {
  animation: buttonPress 0.1s;
}

@keyframes buttonPress {
  0% {
    transform: scale(1);
  }
  50% {
    transform: scale(0.95);
  }
  100% {
    transform: scale(1);
  }
}
```

In this example, when the button is pressed or in focus, the animation named "buttonPress" is activated. This animation scales the button down by setting the `transform` property to `scale(0.95)` at 50% of the animation duration and then returns it to the original scale. The `transition` property adds a smooth transition effect to the transform property, making the button scale down and up smoothly.

Feel free to adjust the animation duration (0.1s in this example) and the scale values to achieve your desired effect.

You're correct, the `:focus` pseudo-class may not be necessary for the button press effect, as it is primarily used for keyboard interactions. If you want the button press effect to trigger only when the button is clicked (not hovered or focused), you can remove the `:focus` pseudo-class from the CSS. Here is an updated example:

```css
.gen-button {
  /* existing styles */
  transition: transform 0.1s;
}

.gen-button:active {
  animation: buttonPress 0.1s;
}

@keyframes buttonPress {
  0% {
    transform: scale(1);
  }
  50% {
    transform: scale(0.95);
  }
  100% {
    transform: scale(1);
  }
}
```

With this CSS, the button press effect will only trigger when the button is actively being clicked, and not when it is being hovered or focused. Again, feel free to adjust the animation duration and scale values to achieve your desired effect.

